post_text:
NUSD is applying for the Nita M. Lowey 21st Century Community Learning Centers (21st CCLC) Grant in order to provide additional learning opportunities for students and the community.

If awarded, this grant supports the implementation of additional value-added activities for students and families alike outside of the school day. Some of the activities being considered are not limited to the following: additional tutoring services, open library dates, parent/child classes, STEM opportunities, clubs, gymnastics and/or fitness classes, etc.

These opportunities would be in addition to the current after school activities offered by Desert Oasis and Nadaburg Elementary. More information can be found at: https://www.azed.gov/21stcclc/whatis21stcclc/
shared_text:
AZED.GOV
What is the 21st Century Community Learning Centers Grant?
text:
NUSD is applying for the Nita M. Lowey 21st Century Community Learning Centers (21st CCLC) Grant in order to provide additional learning opportunities for students and the community.

If awarded, this grant supports the implementation of additional value-added activities for students and families alike outside of the school day. Some of the activities being considered are not limited to the following: additional tutoring services, open library dates, parent/child classes, STEM opportunities, clubs, gymnastics and/or fitness classes, etc.

These opportunities would be in addition to the current after school activities offered by Desert Oasis and Nadaburg Elementary. More information can be found at: https://www.azed.gov/21stcclc/whatis21stcclc/

post_text:
Good Morning Nadaburg Unified School District Parents, Guardians, Staff and School Community:

The health, safety and well-being of our students, families and staff is our top priority. NUSD has plans in place for various actions that may be required in response to the COVID-19 (Coronavirus) and will take immediate action, as needed, to ensure the safety of our students and staff. Administration is preparing a communication to be released later this afternoon regarding our plans in case of a mandatory extended closure beyond Spring Break.

As recommended by health officials and the ADE, we are asking that students and staff stay home when they are sick and everyone should be practicing healthy hygiene habits. We are sanitizing our schools and buses regularly as a precaution. We have purchased and installed hand sanitizer dispensers in main hallways on both campuses and central office.

Please remember that at this time there are no confirmed cases of Coronavirus in our district. Please know that we are closely monitoring the situation.

Thank you,

Dr. Aspasia Angelou
Superintendent

Dear Nadaburg USD 81 School Community:

I want to extend my heartfelt gratitude to all our volunteers who worked to pass this historic bond. It is historic not because of the amount of funding, but what it will mean to our students, families, and local businesses to have a well-planned PreK12 district. We have the opportunity to create innovative and relevant programming so students are prepared for the future that interests them.

This was a hard decision for many and we respect that.

Thank you, All, for a record turnout and your support.

Dr. Aspasia Angelou
Superintendent

While our students enjoyed their day off, our District teachers and staff participated in our September professional development training session of the school year. Leading our district-wide initiative to improve writing across all subject areas this morning is Lisa Buccigrosse from Ottawa University. Teachers also are following a personal pathway. Options for this afternoon included National Board Certification; Gifted Strategies/Endorsement; Instruction Best Practices using the LOI; Writing in the Specials Areas; and Social Emotional Development.

As we approach the November 5th election date, the Nadaburg Unified School District No. 81 Governing Board has called for a school bond from the public, as we continue to pursue the vision of a local PK-12 education system for our community. The Governing Board has requested that the AZSFB present to the Nadaburg Governing Board how they are capable of helping us realize this plan.

Your are invited to attend the School Board meeting on Sept. 11th, 2019, at 6:30 pm, 32919 Center Street, to hear their presentation.

Desert Oasis Elementary accelerates individual student achievement across several grade levels using the Multi-Classroom Leader philosophy of Opportunity Culture. Expanding the reach of highly performing teachers to all students is the backbone of a teaching philosophy that changes the traditional classroom into a learning culture that focuses on individual student learning.
